            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Anil Sharma\u2019s life is a study in bridging two worlds. Born in Fremont to first-generation Indian immigrants, he grew up in the shadow of Silicon Valley\u2019s pragmatic ambition. His father, a software engineer, envisioned a similar path for Anil, filled with logic and lucrative code. But it was his mother, a homemaker who filled their suburban home with the vibrant colors of her saris and the intricate melodies of classical sitar music, who quietly nurtured his soul. For Anil, art wasn't a frivolity; it was an essential, structured system, as complex and beautiful as any algorithm.\n\nHis choice to pursue a Bachelor's in Arts Management was a quiet rebellion, a compromise between his father\u2019s practicality and his own passion. He landed an internship at SFMOMA during college and never truly left. He found his calling not in creating art, but in creating the space for it to be seen. Anil excelled at untangling the logistical knots of multi-million-dollar exhibitions, coordinating everything from international shipping to the precise lighting on a sculpture. His turning point came during the monumental Matisse/Diebenkorn exhibition; while curators debated aesthetics, Anil was the calm center of the storm, managing the complex operations that made the show a seamless success. His promotion to Director of Operations followed two years later.\n\nToday, Anil\u2019s life is a curated balance. He lives with his partner of eight years, David, an urban planner for the city, in a tastefully minimalist apartment in Hayes Valley. His 2.8-mile commute on the Muni F-line is a daily ritual, a time to observe the city\u2019s kinetic energy before immersing himself in the controlled environment of the museum. Evenings are often spent trying new restaurants in their neighborhood or hosting small dinner parties.\n\nAt 43, Anil feels a deep sense of accomplishment, but he isn't complacent. His dream is to pioneer a new wing at SFMOMA dedicated to digital and interactive art, a nod to the tech world he sidestepped but never fully abandoned. He aspires to create a legacy that makes the institution more accessible and dynamic, ensuring that the next generation, regardless of their background, can find their own story within its walls."
